msgid "Setting Up a Scene"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:9
msgid "Scene Settings and Project Default Settings"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:10
msgid ""
"When you start working on a scene, automatically it will belong to the "
"current project, inheriting its settings and default folders. In this way"
" all the scenes belonging to a project are created with the same "
"settings, assuring the consistency of the production (see  :ref:`Managing"
" Projects <managing_projects>`  )."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:12
msgid ""
"Settings concern different tasks you may perform in OpenToonz, such as "
"the scanning, or cleanup process, the camera size and resolution, the "
"frame rate, the output options, etc. They can be accessed in dialogs you "
"can open with commands available in the related menu; for example the "
"scan and cleanup settings commands are available in the Scan & Cleanup "
"menu."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:14
msgid ""
"Settings for a particular scene can always be changed independently from "
"the other ones, and will be automatically saved when the scene is saved."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:16
msgid ""
"If you want to change the default values you can save current scene "
"settings as default, so that all new scenes created for that project will"
" have those values."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:18
msgid "**To save current scene settings as project default settings:**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:20
msgid ""
"Select File  →  Save Default Settings: all the settings from the current "
"scene will become the project default."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:26
msgid "Choosing the Working Unit"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:27
msgid ""
"Positions, distances and sizes can be expressed in several units of "
"measure: inches, millimeters, centimeters, fields and pixels."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:29
msgid ""
"The field unit is equal to 1/2 inch on the horizontal dimension, and it "
"depends on the A/R set in the field guide information of the Scene "
"Settings... dialog on the vertical dimension (see  :ref:`Using the Viewer"
" <using_the_work_area>`  ). For example if the A/R value is 1.77778, two "
"horizontal fields are equal to an inch, while one vertical field equals "
"to an inch divided by 1.77778."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:31
msgid ""
"In the Files  →  Preferences  →  Interface dialog you can set the "
"following default units:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:33
msgid ""
"The Unit is used to display all measures in text fields, and applied when"
" moving or changing the size of stage objects."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:35
msgid ""
"The Camera Unit is used to display and define the camera size in the "
"Xsheet  →  Camera Settings... dialog (see  :ref:`Defining Camera Settings"
" <defining_camera_settings>`  )."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:37
msgid ""
"You can also express values in an unit different from the default one by "
"entering any of the following units and abbreviations: in, inch, \" , ' '"
" (two apostrophes), cm, mm, fld, field and px, after the input value "
"itself. As soon as the value is entered it's converted in the default "
"unit."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:39
msgid ""
"If a value without a specific unit is used, it is supposed to be "
"expressed in the default unit."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:41
msgid "**To set the default working units:**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:43
msgid "Choose File  →  Preferences  →  Interface."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:45
msgid "Do one of the following:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:47
msgid "In the Unit option menu choose the unit you want to use as default."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:49
msgid ""
"In the Camera Unit option menu choose the unit you want to use to express"
" the camera size."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:55
msgid "Setting the Frame Rate"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:56
msgid "|scene_settings|"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:58
msgid ""
"The frame rate is the number of frames per second of animation, and has "
"to be set according to the type of output you have to render, for "
"instance it should usually be 24 for cinematic production, 25 for PAL "
"output, or 30 for NTSC."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:60
msgid ""
"The current scene frame rate can be set in the Scene Settings... dialog, "
"and it is displayed in the bottom bar of any Viewer pane. In case the "
"play back is activated, the actual frame rate is displayed on its left."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:62
msgid ""
"Apart from affecting the playback speed when previewing or rendering a "
"scene, the frame rate also determines the frame count of an audio file "
"when it is imported into the Xsheet (see  :ref:`Creating a Soundtrack "
"<creating_a_soundtrack>`  )."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:64
msgid ""
"Even if a scene has been composited with a specific frame rate for a "
"certain output, it is possible to render it out at a different frame rate"
" by using the Stretch from FPS: To: option in the Output Settings  →  "
"Other Settings dialog (see  :ref:`Choosing the Output Settings "
"<choosing_the_output_settings>`  )."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:66
msgid "|stretch_fps_to|"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:69
msgid "**To set the frame rate:**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:71
msgid "Choose Xsheet  →  Scene Settings..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:73
msgid "In the Frame Rate text field set the frame rate value."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:79
msgid "Defining Camera Settings"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:80
msgid "|camera_settings|"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:82
msgid ""
"The Current Camera Settings dialog, that can be opened from the Xsheet "
"menu, contains parameters for defining the current camera frame size and "
"resolution."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:84
msgid ""
"More than one camera can be defined for each scene, in order to have "
"different output resolutions, or to shot only a particular area of the "
"scene (see  :ref:`Using the Stage Schematic <using_the_stage_schematic>`"
"  )."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:86
msgid ""
"The camera frame size can be expressed in any unit, but will be "
"visualized in the default one chosen in the Preferences  →  Interface "
"dialog (see  :ref:`Choosing the Working Unit <choosing_the_working_unit>`"
"  )."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:88
msgid "In OpenToonz the Camera is defined by different parameters:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:90
msgid ""
"X (Width) and Y (Height) frame size of the camera, expressed in the "
"default Camera Unit (usually inches)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:92
msgid "A/R is the aspect ratio value resulting by dividing Width/Height."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:94
msgid "X and Y resolution Pixels of the resulting image frame seen by the camera."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:96
msgid ""
"X and Y DPI values, calculated using the standard formulas: "
"XDpi=XPx/Width, and YDpi=YPx/Height. This two fields can be forced to "
"have the same value, by activating the equal-sign button between them."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:98
msgid ""
"When inserting a value in one field, the others change accordingly as "
"needed for having a consistent camera. You can decide which set of values"
" has to be considered fixed by OpenToonz. The lock-shaped buttons and the"
" radio buttons at the leftmost column of the camera parameters, let you "
"select which column and row of values has to be preserved by OpenToonz, "
"while changing the others as needed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:100
msgid ""
"The **Use Current Level Settings** button let you set the camera for "
"framing exactly the content of the selected level. Just press this button"
" and OpenToonz will calculate the appropriate values for the camera."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:102
msgid ""
"Camera resolutions can also be selected from a list of predefined camera "
"settings. You can add any camera preset you define to the list, as well "
"as remove any predefined camera from it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:104
msgid ""
"The predefined cameras list is saved in the file ``reslist.txt``  stored "
"in the projectroot (see  :ref:`Setting the Projectroot "
"<setting_the_projectroot>`  )."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:106
msgid "**To add a preset camera resolution:**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:108
msgid "Set the resolution and A/R for the camera you want to save."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:110
msgid "Click the **Add** button on the right of the preset cameras list."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:112
msgid "Assign a name to the camera resolution and click the **OK** button."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:114
msgid "**To remove a preset camera resolution:**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:116
msgid ""
"Select the camera resolution you want to remove in the preset cameras "
"list."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:118
msgid "Click the **Remove** button on the right of the preset cameras list."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:124
msgid "Color Calibration using Look-up Tables"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:126
msgid "|3dlut|"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:128
msgid ""
"OpenToonz can manage the previsualization of color through the use of 3D "
"Look-up Tables. By applying a 3D LUT file, properly configured for the "
"current display monitor, it will be possible to work on different color "
"spaces, such as `Rec. 709 <https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rec._709>`_, "
"`DCI-P3 <https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DCI-P3>`_ or `Rec. 2020 "
"<https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rec._2020>`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:130
msgid ""
"Once a 3DLUT is active, all colors displayed on Viewer, Combo Viewer, "
"Flipbook, Color Model, Palette, and Style Editor will be corrected."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:132
msgid ""
"Currently, only the .3dl file format is supported. It must follow "
"specification written `here "
"<http://download.autodesk.com/us/systemdocs/help/2009/lustre_ext1/index.html?url=WSc4e151a45a3b785a24c3d9a411df9298473-7ffd.htm,topicNumber=d0e8061>`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:134
msgid ""
"Currently, only the Windows version of OpenToonz can detect the currently"
" connected monitor. For other platforms only one 3D LUT file can be "
"applied for any type of monitors. (Even on Windows, connecting multiple "
"different monitors at the same time is not supported for now. It will "
"only identify the first registered monitor)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:136
msgid ""
"PLEASE NOTE: At the moment, using Plastic deformation together with this "
"feature causes a display issue such that the deformed image is not shown "
"in *Camera Stand* mode of the Viewer."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:138
msgid "**To apply a 3DLUT file for previsualizing color:**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:140
msgid "Choose File  →  Preferences...  →  Interface."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:142
msgid "Activate the **Color Calibration using 3D Look-up Table** option."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:144
msgid ""
"In the **3DLUT File for [monitor]:** option, press the file browser "
"button to navigate and select the desired .3DL file."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:146
msgid "Restart OpenToonz for the changes to take effect."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:152
msgid "Assigning Memory for the Undo Operations"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:153
msgid ""
"All the operations performed in the software can be undone by using the "
"Edit  →  Undo command, even to go back for several steps."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:155
msgid ""
"Undo operations require computer memory in order to be performed, and "
"some of them may require more memory than some others, according to their"
" complexity."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:157
msgid ""
"To prevent most of the computer memory to be used by undo operations "
"while you work, a situation that slows down the software performance, it "
"is possible to set a limit for it by specifying the Undo Memory Size (MB)"
" in the Files  →  Preferences  →  General dialog."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:159
msgid ""
"As soon as the limit is reached, the oldest undo operations will be "
"discarded to make room for the new ones."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:165
msgid "Optimizing the Memory Usage"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:166
msgid ""
"When working with Raster images, predominantly being animation levels "
"scanned with OpenToonz or GTS, an extensive usage of computer memory may "
"be required during the cleanup, painting and rendering processes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:168
msgid ""
"After a certain amount of time the computer performance may worsen, as "
"the memory gets fragmented because of the several writing and reading "
"accesses. To prevent this behavior, the Minimize Raster Memory "
"Fragmentation* option can be activated in the Files  →  Preferences  →  "
"General dialog. When activated, a section of computer memory is reserved "
"and used only for operations concerning Raster images."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:170
msgid ""
"If you are working mainly with vector images, that have been drawn inside"
" OpenToonz, this option should be deactivated, as the reserved memory "
"section would be otherwise unused by the computer."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/setting_up_a_scene.rst:172
msgid "The change set for this option is valid only after OpenToonz is restarted."
msgstr ""

